column5: I installed about half of Cheetah Mobile's apps like Clean Master, Battery Doctor, and others. Samsung Galaxy S III Android 4.4.2 KitKat.  I have uninstalled all of Cheetah Mobile's apps with the exception of their launcher, Piano Tiles 1 &2, and Dancing Line.  My phone is performing good as it was back in 2012 when it was new.

I tried all three (that's right, ONLY 3 models for Vizio are compatible) and not a single one worked. There were very, very few models available overall. Not to mention it was a hassle to use and navigate the app, and there were WAY many ads. This rendered the functionality borderline unusable. I won't pay for a full version to remove agressive ads when the app is clunky and wont even connect my devices. I will update my review only IF they make it easier to navigate, add more compatible models, and tone down the ads a bit. Im okay with some ads in exchange for free services, but they were intrusive and much too frequent. It would've been decent if it worked because it is compatible with Alexa and smartwatches. Oh well, I guess I'll keep looking.

After it finally appears I click Stop app and it kills it. But then, after its done and I click OK, it reappears and has to be killed all over again. column5: â˜… PROS ğŸ‘ğŸ˜Š: 1. Simplicity. 2. The One and Only Ads-Free Battery App for Android. 3. Capability to kill the battery drainer Apps manually. 4. Freeware. â€¢ â˜† CONS ğŸ‘â˜¹ : 1. It just like an informative App showing the battery status, just like the Android's built-in battery manager. It has no battery management system (optional management modes) to prolong battery life. 2. No Battery Temperature feature. 3. Surprisingly, it doesn't support Fast Charging, so it fails to show the correct battery charging remaining time. It is annoying. 4. It doesn't display battery trickling process. Many Users would like to know the whole of charging process. 5. It has no Battery Charging Wallpaper to show battery status and charging status right after plugged in.

Not sure if I'm right but it seems like every time I have this app on my phone my battery dies even faster, one time I left my phone at about 90% battery life and in the morning my phone was off dead with no battery so I was late for work and had to charge my device. I haven't really had a problem since I uninstalled this application, I'm sure it's a misunderstanding or something that I can't explain. I would recommend to try this app if you are really experiencing major battery issues and see if it works for you, don't just read a negative review and skip because Kaspersky is genuinely a decent company from my (years) experience. The other problem I had with this app was that it stopped applications only on my command and it was only a quick stop, not permanent, you could do all of that by just going into the apps settings and stopping it. The UI is nice and clean with no advertisements, obviously. Overall Kudos for the effort, I'd be happy if I had some support with the battery draining issue.

column1: Battery Doctor-Battery Life Saver & Battery Cooler
column5:
I'm not really sure if this app does what it says it does. I did not notice 
any appreciable difference. What I did notice is that the second I started 
this app more than 20 internet transactions occurred. And that happened 
before I was able to shut off its internet access. Now why would it want 
internet access but not list it in the permissions? I could understand a 
couple of Internet request to see if there's something new you need. But 
the amount of internet activity suggests something more along the lines of 
data mining. I can't prove that. I can only prove that it accesses the 
internet a lot. I have check the permissions access list located at the 
very bottom of the Google store app page. This app want so many permissions 
that it simply does not need. To me that suggests this app is doing some 
data mining. It may do what it says it does, but it also does a lot more 
you may not want.

column5: So I'll start by saying I got this app to 1 - see which apps are using up the most battery, and 2 - to try and prolong my battery life. The app to me feels almost like some sort of Chinese scam app. A lot of stuff is in broken English and half the features don't really seem to do anything (such as optimizing your phone, it will always say there's issues even if you scanned 1 minute ago. Just as well I cannot see which apps are draining my battery, so the app is virtually useless. But I have yet to mention the worst feature yet, the ads. They are so intrusive, and I'm not talking about just when you have the app open, though there is plenty of that. Imagine you get off work, pull your phone out and unlock it, and you're greeted with ads that you have to close before you can actually use your phone. It's a really nice feature. I think I'll spend 3 dollars on the other battery app that doesn't make my phone feel like it's got a virus on it.

column5: 12/21/2017 update: Obnoxious, intrusive ads override "silent" setting on my phone. Unacceptable! Downgraded from 5 stars to 2 stars and uninstalled. I will do that to every single app with this "feature", will not patronize those advertisers, and have so stated publicly on Facebook. Let's send that message to ALL developers. I would rather pay for an app with no ads than deal with a free one that takes control of my phone like that.  Previous review: Reins in power usage as battery runs down. Monitors battery charging to maximize battery life. Lets you create power saving profiles. What more could you want from a battery saver app? Update: I especially like the new feature to identify and optimize apps that repeatedly restart and drain power. That was one of the mysteries that remained after taking care of the more obvious stuff (like turning off GPS and Bluetooth when not in use, reducing screen brightness, shortening time before screen shutoff, etc.).

Excellent app, one small bug, one missing feature, read my review. This app is a must have for any owner of a Samsung smart tv, it has almost all the options found on the real remote control and it allows you to control your tv from anywhere in the house. So far I only have one problem, I get "import failed " when I try to import channels from my Samsung F5300, it would be great if the developer could fix this bug. Another good idea would be to be able to open from the app the multimedia gallery on the phone and play it to the tv (like in the app Samsung TV Media from ZappoTV), this way I don't have to switch between apps when I want to play a different song or adjust the sound volume. This option could be implemented as a tab in the app that lets the user view his gallery and click at the file he wishes to be played on the tv. Thanks again to the developer for his great work, I give 5 stars because this great app is free. Nexus 4 KK4.4.3

column1: Battery Doctor-Battery Life Saver & Battery Cooler
column5: What....are you joking me?   Why the heck wasn't this included with my phone when i first got it??  Honestly...... Got a new phone in March and it worked just fine.  By April i had added a weather app and 2 games. The next thing i know i'm charging my phone morning, noon and night.  It was always warm (like a Hot Pad in my pocket), and every time i needed it - it's flashing "recharge needed".   Searched the web to find the problem only to find a LOT of people had the same trouble. Also found people recommending something called Battery Doctor.  I was skeptical at first....but i was desperate and needed a working phone NOW.  I tried it and in about 2 hours my phone stopped over heating.  I thought, "COOL" (literally).  It was back to working the way it did fresh out of the box ....AND i could add some new apps. Really...this is a necessary app for any phone.  I just let it take over and now my phone is actually BETTER than when i first got it.  I'm not kiddin' !!!

column5: Whatever you do don't get this ever! This is coming from a Galaxy Note 9. Every 30 seconds to 4 minutes it's just annoying pop ups and not-needed notifications. First it's fine, then it messes with your home screen adjustments, pauses stuff you watch or play, and distrubts and annoys you. Imagine being at a party playing music on a speaker from your phone and having to press play in the middle of a song when your phone for no reason stops. If you want to uninstall the app it doesn't go away. Force stop doesn't work either. It latches on like a virus to any app on your phone and manifests to that. It camouflages itself inside apps that you may use or not use at all. You have to get rid of apps one by one and see if it will go away. This could mean some of your most important apps. If you successfully get rid of the right one it should immediately stop the ads and notifications. If you can't find it or it doesn't work, you'll have to back up your apps and wipe your phone clean. I'm saving anyone who wants to get this. Don't get it, you'll hate it and regret it.

UPDATE 120418: Changing my review from 1 Star to 4. As I accidentally came to understand this app better, found that the only time the app is prepared to kill unnecessary background apps is when the device is not being charged. That is when the button to kill apps turns green, showing ready for use. This app can use significant power when overriding other apps to shut them down, but to be fair, I don't think that can be helped. I only wish this app had the option to continually monitor & kill unnecessary apps, ALL the time rather than needing manual prompting. Nevertheless, it accomplishes its advertised purpose; you just have to keep an eye on it and keep pushing the button every time it turns green, if you want to keep the other apps dormant. ********* The only thing that works in this app is the battery life notification. The 'button' to kill background apps doesn't work, nor does the app do this itself anyway. When first installed received a notice that so many apps we're stopped, then nothing. It gives you the option to opt out certain apps from being stopped, but no indicators of what's running it what's been stopped. If for some insane reason your phone doesn't have a battery life advisor in the notification bar, this would work well. Just don't depend on it for killing background apps or providing information to that effect.
